# **ğŸ”· AWS CloudShell â€“ A Fully Managed Command Line Interface (CLI) in AWS**  

## **ğŸ“Œ What is AWS CloudShell?**  
AWS **CloudShell** is a **browser-based command-line interface (CLI)** that provides an **instant Linux shell** for interacting with AWS services. 
It comes **pre-installed with AWS CLI, Python, Node.js, and other development tools**, 
allowing users to execute AWS commands **without needing to install CLI tools on their local machines**.

âœ… **Pre-authenticated AWS CLI** (No need to configure credentials)  
âœ… **No Setup Required** (Runs instantly in the AWS Management Console)  
âœ… **Persistent Home Directory (1 GB storage per region)**  
âœ… **Secure & Private (Runs in a temporary environment per session)**  
âœ… **Supports Multiple AWS Regions**  

---

## **1ï¸âƒ£ AWS CloudShell Features & Benefits**
### **ğŸ”¹ Key Features**
âœ”ï¸ **Pre-installed AWS CLI & Tools** â€“ No need to install anything locally.  
âœ”ï¸ **Secure & IAM-Managed** â€“ Uses IAM permissions for authentication.  
âœ”ï¸ **Persistent Storage** â€“ Stores **up to 1 GB** per region.  
âœ”ï¸ **Supports Multiple Programming Languages** â€“ Comes with **Python, Node.js, Bash, and PowerShell**.  
âœ”ï¸ **Access to AWS Services** â€“ Use it to interact with **EC2, S3, Lambda, and more**.  

### **ğŸ”¹ Benefits**
| Feature | Benefit |
|---------|---------|
| **No Local Installation** | Works in the AWS Console; no need to install AWS CLI. |
| **Pre-authenticated** | Automatically uses IAM permissions; no manual credential setup. |
| **Multi-Region Access** | Can operate in different AWS regions. |
| **Persistent Storage** | 1 GB home directory per region (retained between sessions). |
| **Secure Environment** | Temporary session-based shell with IAM-based access control. |

---

## **2ï¸âƒ£ How to Access AWS CloudShell?**
### **ğŸ”¹ Opening CloudShell in AWS Console**
1ï¸âƒ£ **Sign in** to your **AWS Management Console**.  
2ï¸âƒ£ Click the **CloudShell icon** (ğŸ”³) in the top-right navigation bar.  
3ï¸âƒ£ CloudShell **opens in a new terminal window** within the AWS console.  

### **ğŸ”¹ Starting CloudShell via CLI**
You can launch AWS CloudShell directly using the AWS CLI:
```bash
aws cloudshell create-session
```

---

## **3ï¸âƒ£ CloudShell vs. AWS CLI vs. EC2 Bastion**
| Feature | AWS CloudShell | AWS CLI (Local) | EC2 Bastion Host |
|---------|---------------|----------------|----------------|
| **Setup** | No setup required | Requires installation | Requires EC2 setup |
| **Authentication** | Pre-authenticated | Requires manual credential setup | Requires SSH keys |
| **Security** | IAM-based access | IAM or credential file | SSH/RDP (less secure) |
| **Persistence** | 1 GB storage per region | Depends on local setup | Persistent (as long as EC2 runs) |
| **Cost** | Free | Free | EC2 instance cost applies |
| **Best For** | Quick AWS CLI access | Advanced local scripting | Private network access |

---

## **4ï¸âƒ£ CloudShell Usage: Common AWS CLI Commands**
### **ğŸ”¹ Check AWS Identity**
```bash
aws sts get-caller-identity
```
ğŸ”¹ Returns IAM role details for the current session.

### **ğŸ”¹ List S3 Buckets**
```bash
aws s3 ls
```
ğŸ”¹ Shows all S3 buckets in the current AWS account.

### **ğŸ”¹ Start an EC2 Instance**
```bash
aws ec2 start-instances --instance-ids i-0abcdef1234567890
```

### **ğŸ”¹ Stop an EC2 Instance**
```bash
aws ec2 stop-instances --instance-ids i-0abcdef1234567890
```

### **ğŸ”¹ Check Available EC2 Instances**
```bash
aws ec2 describe-instances --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].[InstanceId,State.Name,PublicIpAddress]"
```

